resource.name: Purchased Power Adjustment (2016 - Current Year)
resource.description: In order to better align the cost the utility pays to purchase power from its supplier, a purchased power adjustment was added to the customer bills. As the price of power goes up or down, due to open market forces, the utility can raise or lower what it charges its customers to match what it pays for the power.
columns_description: Effective date of the purchased power adjustment (PPA) rate shown
Rate of purchased power adjustment (PPA) calculated monthly on all energy usage

domain_metadata.value: Data obtained from the City of Naperville open data portal (https://data.naperville.il.us)

The Purchased Power Adjustment (PPA) is an adjustment on a customer's bill reflecting the fluctuating supply costs associated with purchasing energy. An increase or decrease in the PPA is dependent on market conditions. The customer's bill will be adjusted monthly to pass the fluctuations in Naperville DPUE's wholesale energy supply costs as a credit or debit. The PPA is based on a rolling six-month average of Naperville's DPUE supply cost for purchased power. It will be calculated monthly on all energy usage (kWH's) for all customer rate classes and applied to a following month's bill.

The purchased power adjustment (PPA) is calculated monthly on all energy usage (kilowatts per hour) for all customer classes, residential and commercial. It is based on a rolling six-month average of electric utility's cost for purchasing power.

The Purchased Power Adjustment (PPA) is an adjustment on a customer's bill reflecting the fluctuating supply costs associated with purchasing energy. An increase or decrease in the PPA is dependent on market conditions. The customer's bill will be adjusted monthly to pass the fluctuations in Naperville DPUE's wholesale energy supply costs as a credit or debit. The PPA is based on a rolling six-month average of Naperville's DPUE supply cost for purchased power. It will be calculated monthly on all energy usage (kWH's) for all customer rate classes and applied to a following month's bill.

The purchased power adjustment (PPA) is calculated monthly on all energy usage (kilowatts per hour) for all customer classes, residential and commercial. It is based on a rolling six-month average of electric utility's cost for purchasing power.

domain_metadata.value: Data obtained from the City of Naperville open data portal (https://data.naperville.il.us)

The Prescription Drug Drop Box Program offers free and easy proper disposal of expired or unneeded prescription drugs and over-the-counter medications, reducing the chance of drugs contaminating water sources or being ingested by minors and animals.  The City provides 24-hour drop boxes at all 10 fire stations and an additional drop box in the main lobby of the police station from 7 a.m. to 8 p.m., Monday through Friday and 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. on Saturdays. The police station drop box also provides a disposal area for medications containing controlled substances.

The data is collected by the Household Hazardous Waste Site Coordinator and delivered to the EMS Bureau Chief who compiles the details.  It is then shared with the Police Department analyst who combines the data with the Police Department medication drop-off site.  It is then placed in a quarterly report provided to the Police Chief and EMS Bureau Chief.  The data is then provided to the public through various outlets.  The data is collected quarterly in the months of March, June, September, & December.  Each station is required to check the drop off box every weekend as part of their daily station duties.  When the box is full, they take the contents to the Household Hazardous Waste site and hand it off to the site supervisor.  The supervisor weighs the bag and logs the weight for the specific station in a master log book.  The supervisor signs the individual station sheet acknowledging that the contents were delivered and logged on the date provided.  The required procedure is noted through a Naperville Fire Department General Order.

The Prescription Drug drop-off data is collected so information can be provided to internal and external stakeholders that shows the amount of unused poisonous medications that have been properly disposed of through a waste site and not disposed of through the city water system.    The data is used to evaluate the need for additional sites in the event the current sites get overloaded.  Additionally, the data is shared with the public to show the importance of safely disposing unused medications which reduces the risk of improper use by persons the medication is not prescribed to.

resource.name: Planted Trees Annual Cost Benefit (2010 - Current Year)
resource.description: The estimated overall benefit of all trees planted in a single year through the Arbor Day Tree Sale compared to the estimated overall benefit these same trees provide at maturity.

domain_metadata.value: Data obtained from the City of Naperville open data portal (https://data.naperville.il.us)

The Arbor Day Tree Sale is a yearly event where trees are available to the public for purchase. There are approximately 500 trees available for sale and range in price from $30.00- $75.00. There are over 40 species available and the trees are planted by the persons who purchase them on private property.

The annual tree sale is organized by the Department of Public Works. The department documents its annual tree sale volumes which are then added to the National Tree Benefits Calculator. NOTE: Specific specie information is not collected annually. The calculations are based on the average benefit of the most common species purchased in past years (e.g., maples, boxelder, catalpa, dogwood, honeylocust, and redbud). The estimates from the National Tree Benefits Calculator do not factor for tree removal or loss. However, the estimate assumes a maturity at 6" to derive benefits which helps to balance the the impact of tree loss in the estimates with trees that grow even larger.

This data is collected as part of the Naperville's effort to document the benefit of its annual tree sale. From a financial standpoint, the tree sale is revenue neutral (e.g., breaks even). This data set provides an estimate of the broader benefit of the sale for the community. The figures provided are estimates.

The Arbor Day Tree Sale is a yearly event where trees are available to the public for purchase. There are approximately 500 trees available for sale and range in price from $30.00- $75.00. There are over 40 species available and the trees are planted by the persons who purchase them on private property.

The annual tree sale is organized by the Department of Public Works. The department documents its annual tree sale volumes which are then added to the National Tree Benefits Calculator. NOTE: Specific specie information is not collected annually. The calculations are based on the average benefit of the most common species purchased in past years (e.g., maples, boxelder, catalpa, dogwood, honeylocust, and redbud). The estimates from the National Tree Benefits Calculator do not factor for tree removal or loss. However, the estimate assumes a maturity at 6" to derive benefits which helps to balance the the impact of tree loss in the estimates with trees that grow even larger.

This data is collected as part of the Naperville's effort to document the benefit of its annual tree sale. From a financial standpoint, the tree sale is revenue neutral (e.g., breaks even). This data set provides an estimate of the broader benefit of the sale for the community. The figures provided are estimates.

resource.name: Purchased Power Adjustment Timeline
resource.description:
Monthly purchased power adjustment added to customer bills. 

In order to better align the cost the utility pays to purchase power from its supplier, a purchased power adjustment was added to the customer bills. As the price of power goes up or down, due to open market forces, the utility can raise or lower what it charges its customers to match what it pays for the power.

domain_metadata.value: Data obtained from the City of Naperville open data portal (https://data.naperville.il.us)

The Purchased Power Adjustment (PPA) is an adjustment on a customer's bill reflecting the fluctuating supply costs associated with purchasing energy. An increase or decrease in the PPA is dependent on market conditions. The customer's bill will be adjusted monthly to pass the fluctuations in Naperville DPUE's wholesale energy supply costs as a credit or debit. The PPA is based on a rolling six-month average of Naperville's DPUE supply cost for purchased power. It will be calculated monthly on all energy usage (kWH's) for all customer rate classes and applied to a following month's bill.

The purchased power adjustment (PPA) is calculated monthly on all energy usage (kilowatts per hour) for all customer classes, residential and commercial. It is based on a rolling six-month average of electric utility's cost for purchasing power.
